title: Support external custom operator schemas on Ubuntu
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
_External custom ops_: Unlike custom operations defined in the onnxruntime code base, the external custom op schemas are compiled into a shared library independently and loaded at runtime. The user should be able to create and use custom ops using prebuilt onnxruntime. The user doesn't need to build onnxruntime to use the external custom ops.

This feature allows the user to directly specify custom op schemas in C/C++ and compile the code into a shared library that may be loaded into python script. See onnxruntime/orttraining/orttraing/test/external_custom_ops for example.

The custom ops need to register with registry in onnxruntime. In order to enable resolving onnx::* and protobuf::* symbols at load-time, onnxruntime needs to expose these symbols. The user code containing custom op schemas may be compiled using the ONNX header files bundled in the onnxruntime wheel. In addition to generated ONNX header files, the wheel contains Protobuf header files.

This PR doesn't add ORT API header files to onnxruntime wheel.

The current changes only support the use-case on Ubuntu platform. This feature requires building onnxruntime with --enable_external_custom_op_schemas and the code changes in this PR are guarded by this flag.

For more details please refer to https://microsoft-my.sharepoint.com/:w:/p/sajandhy/EbwOyIuMyUBEntJYYbjDLtoBDl53eNXlqKV4vfGxNBXb9A
**Motivation and Context**
This use-case is required for 1P users
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
This change enables user to define operator schemas, compile and load into onnxruntime.

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.
https://msdata.visualstudio.com/Vienna/_workitems/edit/1271875

title: Optimize Concat and Split on CUDA to eliminate host-to-device copies when sizes are all the same
body:
This gives +14% end-to-end speed-up on [ProphetNet](https://github.com/microsoft/ProphetNet) model. This optimization is applied for the case all the tensors to be merged or split are the same size along the relevant axis. When there are few tensors (<=32), the tensor device addresses are passed as kernel arguments.

Invoking 4 host-device copy kernels on the default stream adds considerable overhead for the general case. A less urgent optimization would merge these into a single host-device copy. And yet another would avoid it altogether by passing all metadata as kernel arguments - but only if it fits within the 256 byte limit. These operations may further benefit from use of strided tensor formats.

title: Improve GenerateId to reduce hash collision
body:
We see hash collision when models have similar names and are in the same directory.
This PR improves GenerateId function by hashing nodes inputs/outputs besides model path.
1. hash model name instead of model path to address file moving issue.
2. repeat model name hashing to ensure enough characters are hashed and lower the chance of collision.
3. add flags to enable model name, nodes inputs/outputs hashing. It's off by default.
4. generalize GenerateId function to be used by MetaDef ID generator or model ID generator

title: Test parity of a new formula LayerNormalization
body:
**Description**: 

Test a new form of LayerNorm (formula 1):
```
    def layer_norm(x ,weight, bias):
        input_dtype = x.dtype
        x = x.float()
        u = x.mean(-1, keepdim=True)
        y = x - u
        s = y.pow(2).mean(-1, keepdim=True)
        z = y / torch.sqrt(s + self.epsilon)
        return weight * z.to(input_dtype) + bias
```
Result shows that it could achieve same level of parity as nn.LayerNorm (formula 0) in ONNX.

Device | I/O | Layer Normalization Precision | MaxDiff     (Formula 0) | MaxDiff     (Formula 1)
-- | -- | -- | -- | --
CPU | FP32 | FP32 | 2.8e-6 | 2.4e-6
CUDA | FP32 | FP32 | 7.1e-7 | 9.5e-7
CUDA | FP16 | FP32 | 9.8e-4 | 9.8e-4
CUDA | FP16 | FP16 | 3.9e-3 | 3.9e-3



**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Reduce binary size of strided copy used by Concat
body:
**Description**: 
The new strided copy code switched on data type and caused excessively large binary size growth. As we're just copying data, this is data size not data type specific.

* Change the strided copy to switch on data size not data type.
* Move to header and setup to allow reduction of implementation to list of enabled types.
* Setup type reduction for Concat now that it's using this implementation.

Original size in MinSizeRel Windows build was 70KB. 
New setup costs about 5KB per enabled data size (total of ~25KB with all enabled, 10KB for a test build with type reduction enabled and Concat using float and int64_t). 

**Motivation and Context**
Reduce unnecessary binary size growth.

title: Disable some ORT graph optimizers in offline transformers optimization tool
body:
**Description**: 

Disable some graph optimizers that having negative impact on transformers optimization.

Current offline transformers optimization has two passes: one pass is to use OnnxRuntime to run graph optimization, and second pass is to use fusion in Python. In the second pass, we will use symbolic shape inference. 

Currently, there are two issues caused by first pass:
(1) Some contrib ops are not supported by symbolic shape inference. That could block the optimization in the second pass.
(2) Some fusion will change the graph, which will impact fusion in Python since those graph changes might impact fusion.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

Related issue: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8853

title: do not post cuda version mismatch warning if cannot find local cudart…
body: **Description**: It cannot always find local cudart version because cudart.so could be mapped to different names depending on how cuda is installed and the operation systems. We only want to warn the user when it does find local cudart versions and there is no match between local and ort build cuda version. In other cases we do not warn the user.

title: Fix non deterministic of --input_int32 of transformer optimizer
body:
**Description**:
Previous implementation of --input_int32 is non deterministic. The result will depend on optimization result. For example, when EmbedLayerNormalization is not fused, input_ids will not be changed to int32. That confuses users.

Update the logic to always change graph inputs to int32.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

Related issue: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8853

title: Optimize CUDA Kernel for 3D and 4D Transpose
body:
Optimized 4D transpose CUDA kernels so that it can take all permutations, most shapes. 
3D Trasnpose will be treated as 4D Transpose with the leading dimension being 0. 

Transpose120 can be treated as 2D transpose by coalescing the first two dimension. 2D Transpose will be handled by optimized TransposeWithCublas kernel. 

Transpose102 can be treated as specials case of Trasnpose0213 with first dimension being 1. This will handled by optimized Transpose4DParallelizeMultipleElementsPerThreadInInnermostDim kernel.

title: Not to calculate memory for inference
body: To calculate memory usage, a mutex is locked for supporting multi-threading cases. However, in inference mode, it's unlikely we need to know this information. Therefore we disable this function and avoid that lock.
